Bug 2048162 - Follow-up: Fix new mail alert positioning on mixed-DPI multi-monitor setups. r=tobyp

The previous fix for bug 2034322 cached the alert's own screen metrics
to prevent monitor bleed during layout, and the follow-up in this bug
passed the main window's screen geometry to the alert.  Neither approach
handles mixed-DPI setups correctly:

1. The main window's screen values are in its own CSS pixel space (e.g.
   100% scaling).  When the alert opens on a different-DPI monitor
   (e.g. 175%), `window.outerWidth` and `window.moveTo()` operate in the
   alert's CSS pixel space — a different unit system.  Mixing the two
   produces wrong coordinates.

2. The alert should always appear on the primary monitor regardless of
   which screen the Thunderbird window is on (matching ESR 140 behavior),
   not the main window's current monitor.

This patch:

- Queries the primary monitor's geometry directly via
  `nsIScreenManager.primaryScreen.GetAvailRect()`, which returns device
  pixels — a DPI-independent unit.  The alert converts to its current
  CSS pixels on every `snapToCorner()` call, so the math stays correct
  even when the alert changes monitors (and DPI) during layout.

- Adds `left=0,top=0` to the window features so the OS creates the
  alert at the primary monitor's origin from the start.

- Calls `window.sizeToContent()` before the initial snap so the alert
  window fits its content at the current DPI, preventing cut-off text
  or oversized windows.

- Removes the inter-window screen-info passing via `window.arguments`,
  keeping each file self-contained.

Differential Revision: https://phabricator.services.mozilla.com/D309618


